#: src/rust-2018/data-types/union-for-an-unsafe-form-of-enum.md:1
msgid "`union` for an unsafe form of `enum`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/union-for-an-unsafe-form-of-enum.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.19](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.19-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/union-for-an-unsafe-form-of-enum.md:5
msgid "Rust now supports `unions`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/union-for-an-unsafe-form-of-enum.md:14
msgid ""
"Unions are kind of like enums, but they are “untagged”. Enums have a “tag” "
"that stores which variant is the correct one at runtime; unions don't have "
"this tag."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/union-for-an-unsafe-form-of-enum.md:18
msgid ""
"Since we can interpret the data held in the union using the wrong variant "
"and Rust can’t check this for us, that means reading a union’s field is "
"unsafe:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/union-for-an-unsafe-form-of-enum.md:33
msgid "Pattern matching works too:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/union-for-an-unsafe-form-of-enum.md:43
msgid "\"ten\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/union-for-an-unsafe-form-of-enum.md:44
msgid "\"{}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/union-for-an-unsafe-form-of-enum.md:50
msgid ""
"When are unions useful? One major use-case is interoperability with C. C "
"APIs can (and depending on the area, often do) expose unions, and so this "
"makes writing API wrappers for those libraries significantly easier. "
"Additionally, unions also simplify Rust implementations of space-efficient "
"or cache-efficient structures relying on value representation, such as "
"machine-word-sized unions using the least-significant bits of aligned "
"pointers to distinguish cases."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/data-types/union-for-an-unsafe-form-of-enum.md:58
msgid ""
"There’s still more improvements to come. For now, unions can only include "
"`Copy` types and may not implement `Drop`. We expect to lift these "
"restrictions in the future."
msgstr ""
